  "title": "Linking Words: Smooth Speech",
  "learningGoal": "The learner will master 'connected speech' by pronouncing consonant-to-vowel linkages between spatial prepositions (In, On) and indefinite articles (A, An), eliminating robotic word separation.",
  "difficultyLevel": "beginner",
  "baseLanguage": "hi",
  "targetLanguage": "en",
  "estimatedTime": 45,
  "prerequisites": ["en_hi_M1B6_lesson_001"],
  "instructions": "Native English speakers do not speak like robots. Instead of saying 'In ... A ... Box', they link the words together so it sounds like 'I-nuh box'. The consonant at the end of 'In' jumps over to the vowel 'A'. Listen to how smooth it sounds and repeat after the audio.",
  "contentItems": [
    {
      "type": "note",
      "text": "Try to say the first two words as ONE word. 'On a' sounds like 'Aw-nuh'. Let your breath flow continuously."
    }
  ],
